    "summary": "The Siege of Jerusalem (June–July 1099 AD) was the culminating military engagement of the [[event:2220|First Crusade]], in which the exhausted but triumphant Crusader army captured the holy city after a five-week siege, ending four and a half centuries of Muslim rule over Jerusalem and establishing the [[event:2965|Kingdom of Jerusalem]]. The Crusaders, having marched from Constantinople, fought through Anatolia, and endured the grueling seven-month siege of Antioch, arrived before Jerusalem's walls on June 7, 1099, a force diminished by casualties and disease but sustained by religious fervor.\n\nThe assault on July 15, 1099, succeeded after Crusader engineers constructed massive siege towers that allowed warriors to cross onto the city walls. The subsequent massacre of Jerusalem's Muslim and Jewish inhabitants — conducted over several days — was recorded with horror even by some Crusader chroniclers and became one of the defining atrocities of medieval religious warfare. Contemporary accounts describe the Temple Mount running with blood, though modern historians debate the scale of the killing. The capture of Jerusalem was experienced by participants and observers across Christendom as a miraculous divine validation of the crusading project: the holy city, lost to Islam, had been reclaimed. Godfrey of Bouillon, who led the breakthrough, declined the title of King (reportedly saying he would not wear a crown of gold where Christ had worn a crown of thorns) and accepted instead the title 'Advocate of the Holy Sepulchre.' The capture of Jerusalem would be reversed by [[event:2273|Saladin]] at the [[event:2274|Battle of Hattin]] in 1187.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Jerusalem_(1099)",
